## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
complexity
## Location
src/tools/lsp.rs:362-388
## Violation
The Hover branch of `parse_lsp_response` chains five `map_or_else` calls in a single expression that mixes string extraction, object-field extraction, and array-join — all to handle the three LSP `MarkedString | MarkupContent | MarkedString[]` variants. The reader must hold the state of 3+ closures simultaneously.

Quoted (lsp.rs:362-388):
```
        LspAction::Hover => {
            let hover_text = result_data.and_then(|r| r.get("contents")).map(|c| {
                c.as_str().map_or_else(
                    || {
                        c.as_object().map_or_else(
                            || {
                                c.as_array().map_or_else(String::new, |arr| {
                                    arr.iter()
                                        .filter_map(|v| {
                                            v.as_str()
                                                .or_else(|| v.get("value").and_then(|x| x.as_str()))
                                        })
                                        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
                                        .join("\n")
                                })
                            },
                            |obj| {
                                obj.get("value")
                                    .and_then(|v| v.as_str())
                                    .unwrap_or("")
                                    .to_string()
                            },
                        )
                    },
                    str::to_string,
                )
            });
```

Cognitive complexity per SonarQube heuristic exceeds 10 in this expression alone.
## Mandated refactor
1. Define `enum HoverContents { Plain(String), Markup { kind: String, value: String }, Multi(Vec<String>) }` with `Deserialize`.
2. Replace the chained `map_or_else` with a `match contents { ... }` against that enum.
3. Each variant gets a one-line conversion to the rendered string.
